style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion is ageing:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 1950 there were 205 million people aged 60 years or older in the world.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By 2012, the number of older persons increased to almost 810 million.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The number of older people is projected to reach 1 billion in less than ten years and to double</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by 2050, reaching 2 billion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.66pt; padding-left:2.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By 2050, for the first time in history, there will be more people in the world aged 60 and over than children under the age of 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The most rapid increases of population ageing are expected in less developed regions and are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> projected to be over five times higher than those in more developed regions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Of the 2 billion people aged 60 or over in 2050, it is estimated that 80 per cent will live in developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Global population ageing means that more people will be at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk of developing disabling conditions, making it increasingly important to consider ageing as an integral part of disability policy. Older people in developing countries are more likely to have health conditions that are linked to disability than those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in developed countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled people are at risk of premature ageing as early as in their 40s.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ageing and disability</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More than 250 million older people globally experience moderate to severe disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although by no means</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all older people are disa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bled, the prevalence of impairments that can lead to disability increases with age. The link between ageing and an increased prevalence of disability, however, is not inevitable. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Access to healthcare, support services and an enabling environment are import</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ant contributing factors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Statistics show clearly the high prevalence of visual and hearing impairment amongst older people. A total of 110 million people worldwide aged 60 or over have a visual impairment, and more than 80 per cent of all people who are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">visually impaired are aged 50 or older. One-third of people over the age of 65, a total of nearly 63 million, are affected by disabling hearing loss. This is compared to one-fifth of the total population. Two-thirds of these older people live in developing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to the high prevalence of disability within the older population, ageing and the needs of older people with disabilities must be considered as an integral part of development policies that address disability. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability in older age can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have a financial impact on families and communities as well as older people themselves. Functional disability can compound the difficulties faced by older people in developing countries in relation to maintaining an income through work, and if an older pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rson has care needs other family members may be forced to give up their own employment to provide informal care. For example, in 2010 the estimated worldwide cost of dementia was $604 billion, and in developing countries most of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> care </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was shoul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dered by family members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Older disabled people, health and care needs</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Longevity is increasing across the globe, but this is not being coupled with an increase in healthy life expectancy. This means there is a rise in morbidity in later life, the amount</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of time people spend unwell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Many of the disabling health conditions that older people experience are preventable if new approaches to healthy and active ageing are adopted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chronic, non-communicable diseases have been recognised as a leading cause of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">death and disability. They are estimated to account for 66.5 per cent of all years lived with disability in low and middle-income countries</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Older people are at increased risk of developing chronic diseases and related disabilities. It is estimated that 7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 per cent of those estimated to die of non-communicable diseases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> people aged 60 and over.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many older people live with multiple health conditions associated with disability and may have complex needs. Studies show that physical and mental ill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often linked</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A development strategy that addresses disability can only be effective if it encompasses mental and physical disabilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is growing evidence that Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia are on the increase due to an age</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing population. The latest figures on dementia show that global prevalence is higher than previously thought. In 2013 the number of people living with dementia worldwide is estimated at 44 million, and this is expected to rise to 76 million by 2030 and 135</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> million by 2050</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability and illness in older people is often not recognised, and is sometimes dismissed as an inevitable part of the ageing process. The attitude of healthcare staff towards older people can make it difficult to access support or tre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">atment. In the report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ageing in the Twenty-first century</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, an older woman in Tanzania explains that: “Some staff in hospitals are not treating older people well. They claim we are only old but not sick.”</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is evidence in some countries that there is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a shortage of medical staff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are trained to meet older people’s health needs. A report by the International Longevity Centre in South Africa found there were just eight registered geriatric doctors in South Africa to serve an older population of 3.3 million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many older people thems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elves do not see themselves as having a disability, considering reduced mobility and sight or hearing impairment as part and parcel of ageing. As a result, they may be less likely to seek or receive the healthcare and support services which younger people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with disabilities may access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Improving access to healthcare, support and services must include older people with disabilities as well as younger people with disabilities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">UK Government policy</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department for International Development does not have a clear public policy or strategy on disability and recognition of disabled people and older people is practically non-existent across other policy areas. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, in the policy ‘Improving th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e lives of girls and women in the world’s poorest countries’, there is no reference to older women or women with disabilities despite the potential for multiple levels of discrimination. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In another example, the policy ‘Improving the health of poor people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in developing countries’ makes reference to ensuring that health services are free of charge and that there be better access to transport, but there is no explicit reference to the types of difficul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ties disabled and older people, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who may find</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> access diffi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">face</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a third example, the policy ‘Reducing hunger and malnutrition in developing countries’ recognises the impact of chronic malnutrition on children, but does not make reference to the effect of malnutrition on older people’s health or its link </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to disabling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> health conditions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ‘Nutrition for older persons’ section of the World Health Organization’s website states that ‘degenerative diseases such as cardiovascular and cerebrovascular disease, diabetes, osteoporosis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and cancer, which are among the most comm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on diseases affecting older persons, are all diet-affected’. It goes on to state that ‘good health and dietary habits in old age’ can be hindered by the loss of cognitive function and deteriorating vision that older people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK Governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent's </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support for the High Level Panel’s recommendations for a post-2015 sustainable development framework is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> particularly welcome. The transformative agenda "Leave no one behind" and the aspiration that "targets should only be considered 'achieved' if the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y are met for all relevant income and social groups" could provide a step-change in the international community's recognition of disabled and older people as an integral part of international development.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The specific post-2015 commitment to a 'data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">revolution' could also be transformative for our understanding of disability and ageing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concrete steps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are taken to put into action this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recognition that indicators need to be disaggregated by age and disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Recommendations</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to articulate a clear policy and strategy for addressing the needs and rights of disabled people of all ages in its programmes;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID needs to recognise population ageing as a cross-cutting issue that affects all aspects of development. This is increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly important as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> both</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> longevity and the number of older people increase in all parts of the world;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID must place greater emphasis on the importance of non-communicable diseases as part of any strategy to improve the health of people of all ages and as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">part of a wider strategy to reduce the onset of disabling conditions in later life;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID must follow thro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ugh on its post-2015 commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to disaggregate data by age and disability, both in its own evidence gathering, by working with UN partners and suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ting national governments to collect and use disaggregated data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all age groups;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID should increase support for social protection programmes that deliver income security, health, employment and education to disabled people of all ages to help create</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an enabling environment for all;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID must ensure a rights-based approach to disability and ageing is embedded in all relevant programmes and should support the further articulation of the rights of older people by endorsing the creation of a human right</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s convention for older persons.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.05pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="color:#0d2150; font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), Population Division (2012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), Population Division, World Population Prospects: The 2010 Revision, 2011, New York</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), Population Division, World Population </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Prospects: The 2010 Revision, 2011, New York</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), World Population Ageing 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">World Health Organiz</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ation and World Bank, World Report on Disability, Geneva 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> World Health Organiz</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> and World Bank</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10